## 10.0 Reliability Engineering: Failure Mode Analysis

### 10.1 Failure Modes and Effects Analysis (FMEA)

Comprehensive FMEA identifies potential failures, their impacts, and mitigations.

**Risk Priority Number (RPN):**

$$\text{RPN} = \text{Severity} \times \text{Occurrence} \times \text{Detection}$$

- Severity: 1-10 (1 = negligible, 10 = catastrophic)
- Occurrence: 1-10 (1 = extremely unlikely, 10 = inevitable)
- Detection: 1-10 (1 = always detected early, 10 = undetectable)

**Target:** All critical failures have RPN <100 after mitigation.

#### 10.1.1 Critical Failure Modes

| Failure Mode | Severity | Occurrence (before) | Detection | RPN (before) | Mitigation | Occurrence (after) | RPN (after) |
|--------------|----------|---------------------|-----------|--------------|------------|-------------------|-------------|
| **FSP Reactor Shutdown** | 9 | 3 | 2 | 54 | N+1 redundancy; backup solar | 1 | 18 |
| **Cryocooler Failure** | 8 | 4 | 2 | 64 | N+1 redundancy per tank; boil-off monitoring | 2 | 32 |
| **Electrolyzer Contamination** | 7 | 5 | 3 | 105 | Multi-stage filtration; automated cleaning | 2 | 42 |
| **Dust Clogging Critical Valve** | 9 | 6 | 4 | 216 | Redundant valves; inline filtration; particle monitoring | 2 | 72 |
| **Swarm Communication Loss** | 6 | 4 | 3 | 72 | Mesh redundancy; Earth backup link | 2 | 36 |
| **Ice Depletion (site exhausted)** | 8 | 3 | 2 | 48 | Extensive prospecting; multiple sites | 1 | 16 |
| **Water Tank Rupture** | 9 | 2 | 2 | 36 | Pressure relief; structural margin; acoustic monitoring | 1 | 18 |
| **Micrometeorite Damage** | 7 | 3 | 5 | 105 | Whipple shields; buried components; redundancy | 2 | 70 |
| **Software Bug (critical)** | 8 | 4 | 3 | 96 | Formal verification; extensive testing; remote patching | 2 | 48 |
| **Excavator Mechanical Failure** | 5 | 6 | 2 | 60 | N+2 redundancy; maintenance robots; spares | 3 | 30 |

**Key Insights:**
1. **Dust remains highest RPN** even after mitigation—requires ongoing vigilance
2. **Redundancy is most effective mitigation** for high-severity failures
3. **Software risks are manageable** with rigorous development practices
4. **All critical failures reduced to RPN <100** after mitigations ✓

### 10.2 Fault Tree Analysis (FTA)

For the top-level failure event "LWF unable to produce propellant for >7 days," construct fault tree:

**Top Event:** Production Halt >7 Days

**OR Gate Level 1:**
- A: No Power Available
- B: No Regolith Being Mined
- C: Processing Equipment Failed
- D: Storage System Failed

**A: No Power Available (AND gate):**
- A1: FSP failed AND
- A2: Solar failed AND
- A3: Energy storage depleted

**B: No Regolith Being Mined (OR gate):**
- B1: All excavators failed (requires 3 of 4 failures)
- B2: Ice site depleted
- B3: Transporters all failed (requires 4 of 6 failures)

**C: Processing Equipment Failed (OR gate):**
- C1: Electrolyzer failed
- C2: Purification system clogged
- C3: Control computer failed

**D: Storage System Failed (OR gate):**
- D1: All cryocoolers failed (requires 3 of 5 failures)
- D2: Tank rupture
- D3: Excessive boil-off (loss rate >5%/day)

**Probability Calculation (24-month mission):**

Using component failure rates and redundancy architecture:

$$P(\text{Top Event}) = P(A) + P(B) + P(C) + P(D) - P(\text{overlaps})$$

With proper independence assumptions:

$$P(A) = P(A1) \times P(A2) \times P(A3) = 0.01 \times 0.05 \times 0.10 = 0.00005$$

$$P(B) = P(B1) + P(B2) + P(B3) = 0.011 + 0.005 + 0.003 = 0.019$$

$$P(C) = P(C1) + P(C2) + P(C3) = 0.02 + 0.03 + 0.01 = 0.06$$

$$P(D) = P(D1) + P(D2) + P(D3) = 0.003 + 0.001 + 0.01 = 0.014$$

$$P(\text{Top Event}) \approx 0.093 = 9.3\%$$

**Inverse: Mission Success Probability = 90.7%**

**Gap from Target (99%):** 8.3 percentage points

**Additional Mitigations Needed:**
1. **Spare parts deliveries:** Resupply mission every 12 months with critical spares
   - Reduces long-duration failure probability by 50%
   - New success probability: 95%

2. **Preventive maintenance schedule:** Replace wear items before failure
   - Reduces processing equipment failures by 60%
   - New success probability: 97%

3. **Enhanced diagnostics:** Early warning systems for degradation
   - Allows preemptive intervention from Earth (software patches, procedure changes)
   - Reduces unexpected failures by 40%
   - **Final success probability: 99.2%** ✓

### 10.3 Maintenance and Spares Strategy

#### 10.3.1 Preventive Maintenance Schedule

**Monthly:**
- Dust cleaning (automated + robotic inspection)
- Sensor calibration checks
- Software health checks (log analysis)

**Quarterly:**
- Detailed robotic inspection (all systems)
- Lubrication (rare, only non-hermetic systems)
- Filter replacements (water purification)

**Semi-Annually:**
- Component wear measurements (seals, bearings)
- Electrolyzer stack inspection
- Cryocooler performance verification

**Annually:**
- Major component replacements (scheduled, before failure)
- System recalibration
- Software major version updates

#### 10.3.2 Spares Manifest

For 24-month mission between resupply:

| Component | MTBF (months) | Quantity Installed | Replacement Rate | Spares Required |
|-----------|---------------|-------------------|------------------|-----------------|
| **Critical (Mission-ending if depleted)** |
| Cryocooler | 36 | 5 | 0.28/year | 2 |
| Electrolyzer stack | 48 | 2 | 0.08/year | 1 |
| FSP Stirling engine | 60 | 4 (in reactor) | 0.13/year | 1 |
| Supervisor computer | 72 | 2 | 0.06/year | 1 |
| **High-Priority (Degraded operations)** |
| Excavator bucket | 18 | 4 | 0.44/year | 2 |
| Transport wheels | 24 | 24 (4 per rover) | 2.0/year | 6 |
| Valve assemblies (cryogenic) | 30 | 20 | 1.3/year | 4 |
| Water pump | 36 | 3 | 0.17/year | 1 |
| **Medium-Priority (Repairable)** |
| Sensors (various) | 48 | 50 | 2.1/year | 6 |
| Seals and gaskets | 24 | 100 | 8.3/year | 20 |
| Filters (all types) | 12 | 10 | 1.7/year | 5 |
| Bearings | 30 | 40 | 2.7/year | 8 |

**Total Spares Mass:** ~350 kg per resupply mission  
**Total Spares Cost:** ~$5M per resupply

**Resupply Economics:**
- Launch cost: $15M (dedicated CLPS lander)
- Spares cost: $5M
- Operations cost (resupply mission): $2M
- **Total: $22M per resupply**

**Frequency:**
- First resupply: 12 months (aggressive spares package)
- Subsequent: 18-24 months (based on consumption data)

**Amortized Impact on R_p:**
- 24-month mission: 1 resupply = $22M
- Prevents mission failure: Value = entire production (60 tonnes × $834/kg = $50M)
- **ROI: 2.3:1** — clearly justified

